            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is slugging percentage?</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Slugging percentage (SLG)</strong> is a baseball and
                softball statistic that measures how many
                <strong>total bases</strong> a hitter earns per
                <strong>at-bat</strong>. It captures a player’s
                <strong>power</strong>, not just how often they get hits.
              </p>
              <p>
                Unlike batting average, which treats all hits the same, slugging
                percentage gives more weight to doubles, triples, and home runs.
              </p>

              <h2>Slugging percentage formula</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  SLG = <span class="font-semibold">Total Bases</span> ÷
                  <span class="font-semibold">At-Bats</span>
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mt-2">
                  Total Bases (TB) = 1 × 1B + 2 × 2B + 3 × 3B + 4 × HR
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mt-2">
                  SLG = (1B + 2·2B + 3·3B + 4·HR) ÷ AB
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Key points:</strong>
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>AB (at-bats)</strong> excludes walks, hit-by-pitch,
                  and sacrifices.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1B, 2B, 3B, HR</strong> are counts of singles,
                  doubles, triples, and home runs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  SLG is usually shown to <strong>three decimal places</strong>,
                  e.g. <code>.475</code>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Worked example</h3>
              <p>Suppose a player has the following season line:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>AB = 400</li>
                <li>1B = 60</li>
                <li>2B = 25</li>
                <li>3B = 5</li>
                <li>HR = 20</li>
              </ul>
              <p>First, compute total bases:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  TB = 1×60 + 2×25 + 3×5 + 4×20<br />
                  TB = 60 + 50 + 15 + 80 = 205
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Then divide by at-bats:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  SLG = 205 ÷ 400 = 0.5125 ≈ <strong>0.513</strong>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                We would say this hitter has a
                <strong>.513 slugging percentage</strong>, which is strong power
                production.
              </p>

              <h2>What is a good slugging percentage?</h2>
              <p>
                Context matters (league, era, ballpark), but for modern MLB a
                rough guide is:
              </p>
              <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 mt-2">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">
                      Slugging % (SLG)
                    </th>
                    <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Interpretation</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Below .400</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Below-average power</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">.400 – .449</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                      Modest / slightly below average
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">.450 – .499</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Around league average</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">.500 – .549</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Good power hitter</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">.550 – .599</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Excellent power</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2">.600+</td>
                    <td class="px-3 py-2">Elite / MVP-level power season</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <h2>Slugging percentage vs. batting average vs. OPS</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Batting average (AVG)</strong> = H ÷ AB. Every hit
                  counts the same.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Slugging percentage (SLG)</strong> = TB ÷ AB. Rewards
                  extra-base hits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>On-base percentage (OBP)</strong> includes walks and
                  HBP.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>OPS</strong> = OBP + SLG, combining getting on base
                  and hitting for power.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                A player can have a <strong>high AVG but low SLG</strong> (lots
                of singles) or a <strong>modest AVG but high SLG</strong> (lower
                contact, huge power).
              </p>

              <h2>Common questions about slugging percentage</h2>

              <h3>Does slugging percentage include walks?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Walks, hit-by-pitches, and sacrifice bunts/flies do not
                count as at-bats, so they are
                <strong>not</strong> part of the slugging percentage
                calculation. They do matter for
                <strong>on-base percentage</strong>, but not for SLG.
              </p>

              <h3>Can slugging percentage be greater than 1.000?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, especially in small samples. If a player has more than one
                base per at-bat on average (for example, several home runs in a
                handful of at-bats), SLG can exceed 1.000. Over a full season,
                SLG above 1.000 is essentially impossible.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why is it called a “percentage” if it’s written like .500?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Historically, many baseball stats are written as
                <code>.XYZ</code> but called “percentages”. You can think of SLG
                as “bases per at-bat”. A .500 slugging percentage means the
                hitter averages <strong>half a base per at-bat</strong>.
              </p>
            </section>

